  "response": "Okay, finding the absolute cheapest place requires a bit of legwork since prices can fluctuate. However, I can give you a strategy and some likely contenders for the cheapest vitamin B-12 near the University of Washington campus:\n\n**Strategy for Finding the Cheapest B-12:**\n\n1.  **Compare Unit Prices:**  Don't just look at the overall price of a bottle. Pay attention to the **price per dose (e.g., price per pill, per lozenge, per spray).**  This is the only way to compare different forms and dosages fairly.\n\n2.  **Check for Sales & Promotions:**  Many stores have weekly ads, coupons, or loyalty programs that can significantly lower the price.\n\n3.  **Consider Generic vs. Brand Name:** Generic versions are almost always cheaper than brand names and have the same active ingredients.\n\n**Likely Contenders (Near UW Campus):**\n\n*   **Grocery Stores (Target, Trader Joes, Safeway):**\n    *   **Target (U District):** Target typically has a decent selection of vitamins, including their own Up & Up brand. This is a good starting point.\n    *   **Trader Joe's (U District):** Trader Joe's often has good prices on vitamins and supplements, especially their own brand. It's worth checking their selection.\n    *   **Safeway (Roosevelt):** Safeway generally has vitamins, but it may not be the absolute cheapest compared to Target or Trader Joe's.\n*   **Drugstores (Walgreens, CVS):**\n    *   **Walgreens and CVS (various locations near campus):** These stores are convenient, but their prices are often higher than grocery stores or online retailers. However, they frequently have sales or coupons, so check their weekly ads.  Look for generic versions.\n*   **Online Retailers (Amazon):**\n    *   **Amazon:** While not a physical store near campus, Amazon is often the cheapest option, especially if you're willing to buy in bulk. However, consider shipping costs and delivery time.  Prime members get free shipping.\n\n**Specific Suggestions and Things to Check:**\n\n*   **Form of B-12:**  B-12 comes in different forms (cyanocobalamin, methylcobalamin). Methylcobalamin is often preferred.\n*   **Dosage:** Determine the dosage you need before shopping.\n*   **Check for Sales:** Check the weekly ads of Target, Walgreens, and CVS online or in-store.\n\n**How to Find the *Absolute* Cheapest:**\n\n1.  **Visit the Stores:** Physically go to Target, Trader Joes, and Safeway in the U District.  Browse the vitamin aisles and compare the unit prices of B-12 supplements.\n2.  **Check Online:** Check Amazon and any other online retailers you trust, comparing prices.\n3.  **Factor in Transportation:** Consider the cost and time of getting to each store.\n\nGood luck with your B-12 hunt!\n",
